english:
  title: Instructions for the Spotted Mastiff
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your coat bears patterns—are you descended from Panhu of old? Your movements are swift, your mind keen—are you offspring of the Black Dragon? Your paws ring like bells, your snout gleams like lacquer; your joints flow smooth, your sinews taut and strong. Your devotion to our master stirs affection; your duty at the gate brings me pride. For this I cherish your fierce spirit and honor your noble will, keeping you in my home with care and sustenance. Though you are but a humble beast, the spirit of the Great Bear dwells within you—what creature among all things possesses your cleverness and wit?

    Listen well when the master commands—perk up those ears and hear! Bark without restraint and people cease to fear you; bite indiscriminately and ruin shall follow. When officials arrive with three-tiered caps held high, riding in elegant carriages with ornate fittings, their jeweled belts gleaming—when their processions fill the streets with clamor and glitter—do not bark. When urgent decrees arrive, documents that suffer no delay, when the throne thinks of our master and summons him to the palace itself, when the servants rush to fetch him—even in the darkness of night, do not bark. When guests arrive bearing gifts of preserved delicacies and fine wine to honor a learned visitor—do not bark. When scholars come, their books tucked beneath their robes, ready to debate and question our master with endless criticism—do not bark. These are the times you must hold your tongue.

    But listen also to this: there are times to bark and bite. When thieves probe the walls seeking to peek into our home, when they scheme to steal gold and precious things—then bark swiftly, bite swiftly, waste no moment! When strangers come with honeyed words but hidden malice, spying out secrets and spreading poison—then let your voice ring out! When false priests and wicked shamans arrive, eyes gleaming with deceit, performing illusions and tricks to bewitch the household—then sink your teeth into them! When crafty ghosts and mischievous spirits slip through cracks in the darkness, seeking to invade our dwelling—chase them away with fierce barking! When great rats and foxes burrow into our walls—kill them without mercy!

    Guard the pantry and steal no meat; guard the cooking pot and lick not its contents. Do not climb onto the sleeping platform; do not dig up the earth; do not stray from the gate; do not surrender to slumber. When you bear offspring, let them be swift and clever, bearing the chest of a leopard and the tail of a dragon, so that they too may serve our master's grandchildren well.

    Ah! If you heed my words faithfully and remain true to your nature, then when a thousand years have passed and our master ascends to become an immortal, he may yet reward you with elixir and draw you up to heaven itself. Is this not possible? Listen well, listen well—neglect not this charge!
  footnotes:
    - Panhu and the Black Dragon are creatures from ancient Chinese mythology, suggesting noble ancestry and auspicious qualities.
    - The Great Bear (Doushen) refers to a divine constellation spirit, emphasizing the dog's spiritual significance beyond mere animality.
    - The detailed descriptions of officials, scholars, and supernatural beings reflect the specific threats and visitors a noble household might encounter in medieval Korea.
